<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What was the main goal of the Niagara Movement led by W.E.B. Du Bois?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Environmental conservation near Niagara Falls</option>
            <option letter="b">Immediate equal rights for African Americans</option>
            <option letter="c">Gradual economic improvement for blacks</option>
            <option letter="d">Hydroelectric power development</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Niagara Movement, founded in 1905, demanded immediate equal rights and an end to racial discrimination, rejecting Booker T. Washington's more gradual approach to racial equality.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which legislation authorized the government to arrest and deport suspected anarchists and radicals?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The Selective Service Act</option>
            <option letter="b">The Espionage Act</option>
            <option letter="c">The Sedition Act</option>
            <option letter="d">The Immigration Act</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The Sedition Act of 1918 expanded the Espionage Act to allow the government to arrest and deport suspected radicals and anarchists, especially during the Red Scare period.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the primary function of the War Industries Board during World War I?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Recruiting soldiers</option>
            <option letter="b">Coordinating industrial production</option>
            <option letter="c">Censoring newspapers</option>
            <option letter="d">Managing food rationing</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The War Industries Board, led by Bernard Baruch, coordinated industrial production during WWI, converting peacetime factories to war production and setting production priorities.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Why was the Spanish Flu pandemic particularly unusual?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It originated in Spain</option>
            <option letter="b">It mainly affected young, healthy adults</option>
            <option letter="c">It only infected military personnel</option>
            <option letter="d">It was easily cured</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Spanish Flu was unusual because it was particularly deadly for young, healthy adults, unlike typical flu strains that mainly affect the very young and elderly.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the Roosevelt Corollary to the Monroe Doctrine?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">A policy of complete isolation from Europe</option>
            <option letter="b">The right of the US to intervene in Latin America</option>
            <option letter="c">A naval expansion program</option>
            <option letter="d">An alliance with European powers</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Roosevelt Corollary (1904) claimed the right for the US to intervene in Latin American countries to prevent European intervention, extending the Monroe Doctrine's scope.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
